<TITLE> European shares extend gains as credit fears ease </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, July 31 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares hit session highs by midday on Tuesday, on track for their biggest one-day rally in a year, as waning credit concerns boosted bank shares. By 1127 GMT the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was up 2 percent at 1,547.65 points, having risen by as much as 2.2 percent to a session high of 1,548.71 points, its largest one-day gain since July 19 2006. The index had fallen for five straight trading sessions by Monday and is still 5 percent down from the 2007 peak at 1,635.58 points, reached on July 13. London's FTSE 100 index rose 2.4 percent in its largest daily rally so far this year. Frankfurt's DAX gained 1.9 percent and Paris' CAC 40 rose 1.8 percent. Much of the support for European equities came from a sharp rise in US stock index futures and a fall in the iTraxx Crossover index, a key measure of European credit sentiment, which shed about 100 basis points from Monday's life-time highs above 500 basis points. Among leading weighted gainers, HSBC shares rose 2.5 percent, while RBS shares were up 4.4 percent and BNP Paribas up 3.4 percent, putting the DJ Stoxx index of European banking stocks on track for its largest daily rise in a ye
